In MSTest v4, `[ExpectedException]` was **removed**. The replacement is **`Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>()`** (wraps the throwing call in a lambda):

```csharp
// Before (v3):
[ExpectedException(typeof(ArgumentNullException))]
[TestMethod]
public void Validate_NullInput_ThrowsArgumentNull()
{
    Validate(null);
}

// After (v4):
[TestMethod]
public void Validate_NullInput_ThrowsArgumentNull()
{
    Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(() => Validate(null));
}
```

Key differences:
- **`ThrowsExactly<T>`** — matches the exact exception type (same as `[ExpectedException]`)
- **`Throws<T>`** — also matches derived types
- For `async` methods, use `Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<T>`
- You can capture the returned exception to assert on its message/properties

